HOUSE BILL 1623
L2, Q2 6lr3615
By: Montgomery County Delegation
Introduced and read first time: February 21, 2026
Assigned to: Rules and Executive Nominations
Re–referred to: Ways and Means, February 26, 2026
Committee Report: Favorable
House action: Adopted
Read second time: March 7, 2026
CHAPTER ______
1 AN ACT concerning
2 Special Taxing Districts – Village of Drummond – Authority and Organization
3 MC 20–26
4 FOR the purpose of constituting the Village Council of Drummond as the governing body
5 of the special taxing district constituted as the Village of Drummond in Montgomery
6 County; providing for the structure, membership, duties, and obligations of the
7 Village Council; altering the eligible uses of funds derived from the Village’s annual
8 special tax levy; providing for the Village’s annual appropriations process; and
9 generally relating to the authority and organization of the special taxing district
10 constituted as the Village of Drummond in Montgomery County.
11 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
12 The Public Local Laws of Montgomery County
13 Section 65–1 through 65–11
14 Article 16 – Public Local Laws of Maryland
15 (2014 Edition and October–November 2025 Supplement, as amended)
16 BY adding to
17 The Public Local Laws of Montgomery County
18 Section 65–12 and 65–13
19 Article 16 – Public Local Laws of Maryland
20 (2014 Edition and October–November 2025 Supplement, as amended)
EXPLANATION: CAPITALS INDICATE MATTER ADDED TO EXISTING LAW.
[Brackets] indicate matter deleted from existing law.
Underlining indicates amendments to bill.
Strike out indicates matter stricken from the bill by amendment or deleted from the law by
amendment. *hb1623*

2 HOUSE BILL 1623
1 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
2 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
3 Article 16 – Montgomery County
4 65–1.
5 (A) For the purposes of this chapter, the Village of Drummond, Montgomery
6 County, Maryland[, as hereinafter described,] (THE “VILLAGE”) shall constitute a special
7 tax area or district and shall [be deemed and taken to] comprise certain parcels of land,
8 namely: The subdivision in [said] Montgomery County called “Drummond” as per plat no.
9 48, recorded in Plat Book No. 1, one (1) of the land records for [said] Montgomery County,
10 and the adjoining subdivision called “First Addition to Drummond” as per plat no. 89,
11 recorded in [said] Plat Book No. 1.
12 (B) THE VILLAGE COUNCIL OF DRUMMOND, MONTGOMERY COUNTY,
13 MARYLAND (THE “VILLAGE COUNCIL”) SHALL CONSTITUTE THE GOVERNING BODY
14 OF THE VILLAGE.
15 65–2.
16 (a) On and after April 25, 1947, the following described area shall no longer be
17 included within the special taxing area of the Village [of Drummond, Montgomery County,
18 Maryland]: Lots numbered One, Two, and Three in the Village [of Drummond], located at
19 the southwest corner of Wisconsin and Hunt Avenues.
20 (b) The owner or owners of the property in [said] THE area [shall] DESCRIBED
21 IN SUBSECTION (A) OF THIS SECTION MAY not [hereafter] be levied upon for taxes
22 applicable only to the special taxing area of the [said] Village [of Drummond], nor shall
23 any indebtedness of [said] THE special taxing area, incurred after April 25, 1947, be a lien
24 upon the area so removed from [said] THE special taxing area[; provided, that any].
25 (C) ANY future levy for any bond or indebtedness of [said] THE special taxing
26 area, incurred before April 25, 1947, or any extension, refinancing or renewal thereof, shall
27 include the owners of and be a lien upon the property within [said] THE excluded area[;
28 provided, however, that] BUT nothing [herein contained] IN THIS SECTION shall be
29 construed to relieve either the owner or the property in [said] THE area DESCRIBED IN
30 SUBSECTION (A) OF THIS SECTION from the obligation of the tax levy of July 1, 1946.
31 65–3.
32 (A) The [county council for] Montgomery County COUNCIL (THE “COUNTY
33 COUNCIL”) is hereby authorized, empowered and directed to levy and cause to be collected
34 from the property owners at the time of the county tax levy for [the] EACH FISCAL year
35 [commencing July 1, 1916, and ending June 30, 1917, and each succeeding year,] within

HOUSE BILL 1623 3
1 the [said village known as Drummond, as named and created by this chapter,] VILLAGE
2 fourteen cents ($0.14) on each one hundred dollars ($100.00) of the assessable value of the
3 real property other than operating real property of a public utility and thirty–five cents
4 ($0.35) on each one hundred dollars ($100.00) of the assessable value of the personal
5 property and operating real property of a public utility in [said village] THE VILLAGE, to
6 be collected as all other county taxes in [said] THE county are collected[; to be] AND paid
7 over by [said county council] THE COUNTY COUNCIL to the [treasurer of the committee
8 herein authorized to be created, or his successors selected by the majority of the members
9 as said committee, upon said treasurer having been duly selected by a majority of said
10 committee, and giving corporate bond to Montgomery County, Maryland, satisfactory to
11 and approved by the county manager and the county attorney in a penal sum to be fixed by
12 them, conditioned upon the faithful discharge of the duties of said treasurer; the said county
13 council] VILLAGE.
14 (B) THE COUNTY COUNCIL shall [also] order and have paid over to [said
15 treasurer] THE VILLAGE the proportion of the county road tax to be levied and collected
16 in the same manner as though [said] THE Village [of Drummond] was an incorporated
17 town, and the [said village] VILLAGE shall for that purpose[,] be considered by [said
18 county council] THE COUNTY COUNCIL as an incorporated town in [said] THE county[;].
19 (C) THE VILLAGE SHALL USE all of [said] THE funds [to be used directly by or
20 through said committee,] UNDER SUBSECTION (B) OF THIS SECTION exclusively for
21 opening, improving, widening, maintaining, repairing and lighting the streets, roads, lanes,
22 approaches, alleys, sidewalks, parking, drainage, sewerage, sanitation and other village
23 improvements, FOR HIRING EMPLOYEES, and for furnishing police and fire protection,
24 clerical, PROFESSIONAL, and other public service, including the removal AND DISPOSAL
25 of SNOW, LEAVES, ashes, garbage and other refuse[, and the disposal thereof], and for the
26 enforcement of the requirements of all conveyances for properties situated in [said village]
27 THE VILLAGE, [and] for enforcing such building, sanitary and other regulations as [said
28 committee] THE VILLAGE COUNCIL subject to the approval of the [county council]
29 COUNTY COUNCIL may prescribe for [said village] THE VILLAGE, or for any part thereof,
30 AND FOR OTHER PURPOSES DEEMED APPROPRIATE BY THE VILLAGE COUNCIL FOR
31 THE OPERATION OF THE VILLAGE AND THE PROTECTION AND PRESERVATION OF
32 THE PUBLIC HEALTH, SAFETY, AND WELFARE.
33 (D) (1) THE VILLAGE SHALL OPERATE ON AN ANNUAL BUDGET FOR A
34 FISCAL YEAR BEGINNING EACH JULY 1 AND ENDING AT THE END OF EACH JUNE 30
35 OF THE FOLLOWING YEAR.
36 (2) BEFORE ADOPTING AN ANNUAL BUDGET, THE VILLAGE COUNCIL
37 SHALL HOLD A PUBLIC HEARING.
38 (3) THE VILLAGE COUNCIL SHALL PROVIDE THE PUBLIC NOTICE OF
39 AN ANNUAL BUDGET HEARING AT LEAST 10 DAYS BEFORE THE HEARING, INCLUDING

4 HOUSE BILL 1623
1 BY PROVIDING A COPY OF THE PROPOSED ANNUAL BUDGET OR A SUMMARY OF THE
2 PROPOSED ANNUAL BUDGET.
3 (4) THE ANNUAL BUDGET SHALL CONSIST OF A FINANCIAL PLAN FOR
4 THE FISCAL YEAR AND SHALL CONTAIN ESTIMATES OF ANTICIPATED REVENUES AND
5 PROPOSED EXPENDITURES.
6 (5) PUBLIC FUNDS MAY NOT BE EXPENDED WITHOUT FIRST HAVING
7 BEEN APPROPRIATED BY THE VILLAGE COUNCIL.
8 (6) THE VILLAGE COUNCIL MAY AMEND THE BUDGET AND
9 APPROPRIATE FUNDS FROM A RESERVE PROVIDED IN THE BUDGET FROM TIME TO
10 TIME DURING THE FISCAL YEAR TO MEET EXTRAORDINARY OR UNANTICIPATED
11 EXPENDITURES THAT MAY ARISE.
12 (7) THE VILLAGE COUNCIL SHALL HIRE OR EMPLOY A CERTIFIED
13 PUBLIC ACCOUNTANT TO AUDIT THE VILLAGE’S FINANCES.
14 65–4.
15 (A) If in any year the majority of the [said Drummond Citizens’ Committee]
16 VILLAGE COUNCIL shall decide the sum hereinbefore authorized to be taxed and levied
17 is in excess of the amount required for the ensuing year, then [and in that event,] the [said
18 committee] VILLAGE COUNCIL may, on or before April 15 of any year, notify in writing
19 the [county council of Montgomery County] COUNTY COUNCIL to make a reduction in the
20 [said] levy of fourteen cents ($0.14) on each one hundred dollars ($100.00) of assessable
21 value of real property other than operating real property of a public utility and thirty–five
22 cents ($0.35) on each one hundred dollars ($100.00) of assessable value of personal property
23 and operating real property of a public utility, [as hereinbefore provided for,] WITH the
24 amount of [said] THE reduction to be determined by the [said committee] VILLAGE
25 COUNCIL and specified in the [said] notification to the [county council; and upon]
26 COUNTY COUNCIL.
27 (B) ON receipt of [such] A notification UNDER SUBSECTION (A) OF THIS
28 SECTION, the [board of county council of Montgomery County] COUNTY COUNCIL is
29 authorized, empowered and directed to make a levy less than the [said] fourteen cents
30 ($0.14) or thirty–five cents ($0.35) in the amount determined and specified by the [said
31 committee] VILLAGE COUNCIL.
32 65–5.
33 (A) On the first Monday [in] OF EACH May [in the year 1917 and on the same
34 day in each year thereafter], an election shall be held in the [said] Village [of Drummond]
35 for the election of three (3) [committeemen] MEMBERS OF THE VILLAGE COUNCIL, each

HOUSE BILL 1623 5
1 of whom shall have been a resident of [said] THE Village [of Drummond] for AT LEAST six
2 (6) months [previous to said] BEFORE THE election, [and over the age of twenty–one (21)
3 years, the three (3) said committeemen to be and] AND BE AT LEAST 21 YEARS OLD.
4 (B) THE INDIVIDUALS ELECTED SHALL constitute the [Drummond Citizens’
5 Committee] VILLAGE COUNCIL for the ensuing year, each of whom shall qualify within
6 twenty (20) days after [said] THE election by taking the oath prescribed by the Constitution
7 of [Maryland] THE STATE, before an officer of the law duly commissioned to administer
8 [same] THE OATH.
9 (C) (1) The annual election of [said committeemen as herein provided] THE
10 MEMBERS OF THE VILLAGE COUNCIL shall be held [under and] in accordance with the
11 laws of the State [of Maryland], but the returns [thereof] OF THE ELECTION shall be made
12 to the [county council of Montgomery County; all] COUNTY COUNCIL.
13 (2) ALL residents of [said] THE Village [of Drummond for six (6) months
14 previous to said election, and over the age of twenty–one (21) years,] WHO ARE AT LEAST
15 18 YEARS OLD shall be eligible to vote at [such elections; said elections] THE ELECTION.
16 (3) THE ELECTION shall be conducted by UP TO three (3) judges of election
17 [and two (2) clerks, to be] appointed by [said committee, who shall serve without pay; and
18 the polls of said election shall be open from 7:00 p.m. to 9:00 p.m. on the first Monday in
19 May as hereinbefore provided] THE VILLAGE COUNCIL.
20 (D) (1) THE MEMBERS OF THE VILLAGE COUNCIL SHALL SERVE
21 WITHOUT PAY.
22 (2) A MAJORITY OF THE MEMBERS OF THE VILLAGE COUNCIL SHALL
23 CONSTITUTE A QUORUM FOR THE TRANSACTION OF BUSINESS.
24 (3) THE VILLAGE COUNCIL SHALL DETERMINE THE VILLAGE
25 COUNCIL’S RULES AND ORDER OF BUSINESS.
26 (4) THE VILLAGE COUNCIL SHALL MEET AT LEAST 11 TIMES EACH
27 YEAR ON DATES DETERMINED BY THE VILLAGE COUNCIL, EXCEPT THAT THE MAYOR
28 AND THE VILLAGE COUNCIL MAY CALL SPECIAL MEETINGS OF THE VILLAGE
29 COUNCIL.
30 (5) ALL MEETINGS OF THE VILLAGE COUNCIL, REGULAR AND
31 SPECIAL, SHALL BE PUBLIC MEETINGS DURING WHICH MEMBERS OF THE PUBLIC
32 SHALL HAVE A REASONABLE OPPORTUNITY TO BE HEARD, EXCEPT THAT THE
33 VILLAGE COUNCIL MAY HOLD CLOSED SESSIONS, WORK SESSIONS AT WHICH PUBLIC
34 COMMENT MAY BE PROHIBITED, AND SPECIAL PURPOSE MEETINGS AT WHICH ALL
35 PUBLIC COMMENT MAY BE LIMITED TO THE SUBJECT OF THE MEETING.

6 HOUSE BILL 1623
1 (6) THE VILLAGE COUNCIL SHALL KEEP A RECORD OF MEETING
2 MINUTES AND MAKE THE RECORD AVAILABLE FOR PUBLIC INSPECTION.
3 (E) ANY MEMBER OF THE VILLAGE COUNCIL MAY BE REMOVED BY THE
4 COUNTY COUNCIL UPON THE CHARGE OF MALFEASANCE OR MISFEASANCE IN
